        <section id="Raigad Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Raigad Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Raigad Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Raigad Fort, located in the Raigad district of Maharashtra, is a historic hill fort that served as the capital of the Maratha Empire under Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj. It was here that Shivaji was crowned in 1674, solidifying its importance as the center of Maratha administration and military operations. The fort is accessible by a ropeway and offers a glimpse into the rich history of the Maratha kingdom. </p>
            <p>apital of the Maratha Empire:Raigad served as the capital of the Maratha Empire, a significant period in Indian history. 
            Shivaji Maharaj's Coronation:The fort is where Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj was crowned as the king of the Maratha kingdom. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Murud-Janjira Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Murud-Janjira Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Murud-Janjira Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Janjira Fort, also known as Murud-Janjira Fort, is a historical marine fort located off the coast of Murud in Maharashtra, India. It's famous for being one of the strongest marine forts in India and is known for never having been conquered. The fort is situated on an island in the Arabian Sea and is approached by sailboats from Rajapuri jetty. </p>
            <p>Strategic Location:The fort's location on an island in the Arabian Sea provided a natural defense, with the sea acting as a moat. Impregnable Structure:It's renowned for its strong fortifications and towering walls, which resisted numerous attacks from various forces. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Diveagar Beach" class="section">
            <h2>Diveagar Beach</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Diveagar Beach" class="section-image">
            <p>Diveagar Beach, located in the Raigad district of Maharashtra, is a serene and beautiful beach known for its white sand, clear blue waters, and tranquil atmosphere. It's a popular destination for those seeking a peaceful getaway, with opportunities for water sports and stunning sunset views. The beach is lined with coconut groves and beetle nut trees, adding to its picturesque charm. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Jagadishwar Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Jagadishwar Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Jagadishwar Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>The Jagadishwar Temple, located within Raigad Fort, is a significant Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Shiva, revered as Shri Jagadeshwar. It was built by Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj, the legendary Maratha king, after he made Raigad his capital in 1674. The temple is a notable example of Hemadpanthi architecture with Maratha influences, featuring intricate stone carvings and a Nandi statue at the entrance. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Varadvinayak Temple" class="section">
            <h2>Varadvinayak Temple</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Varadvinayak Temple" class="section-image">
            <p>Varadvinayak Temple, also known as Mahad Ganpati, is one of the eight revered Ashtavinayak temples of Lord Ganesha in Maharashtra, India. It's located in Mahad village, Khalapur taluka, near Karjat and Khopoli in Raigad district. The temple is known for its serene atmosphere and spiritual significance, and it's dedicated to Ganesha as the giver of success and bounty. </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Karnala Bird Sanctuary & Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Karnala Bird Sanctuary & Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Karnala Bird Sanctuary & Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Karnala Bird Sanctuary, located near Panvel in the Raigad district of Maharashtra, is a popular destination for birdwatchers, hikers, and nature lovers. It is centered around the historic Karnala Fort, adding a unique historical element to the natural beauty.</p>
            <p>Biodiversity: The sanctuary is a haven for over 222 bird species, including endemic species of the Western Ghats like the Grey-fronted Green Pigeon and Malabar Parakeet. It also hosts 46 migratory species during winter. Rare birds like the Ashy Minivet and Malabar Trogon have been sighted here. Additionally, 114 species of butterflies can be found. Beyond birds and butterflies, other wildlife include wild boar, muntjak, langur, and the four-horned antelope, with a rare leopard sighting documented.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="Matheran" class="section">
            <h2>Matheran</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Matheran" class="section-image">
            <p>Matheran is a charming, car-free hill station in Maharashtra, India, known for its pleasant climate, scenic viewpoints, and the unique Matheran Hill Railway. It's a popular getaway, especially during the cooler months, offering a peaceful escape from the summer heat. </p>
            <p>Viewpoints:Panorama Point (offering 360-degree views), Louisa Point (known for views of Prabal Fort and waterfalls), Echo Point, Monkey Point, and Porcupine Point (Sunset Point) are popular for their scenic vistas. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Takmak Tok" class="section">
            <h2>Takmak Tok</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Takmak Tok" class="section-image">
            <p>Takmak Tok is a historical point on Raigad Fort, Maharashtra, known for its stunning views and execution history. It stands at 1200 feet above sea level and was historically used to punish criminals by throwing them from the cliff. Today, it's a popular tourist attraction offering scenic beauty and a glimpse into the past. </p>
        </section>

        <section id="Sagargad Fort" class="section">
            <h2>Sagargad Fort</h2>
            <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Sagargad Fort" class="section-image">
            <p>Sagargad Fort is a hill fort in Raigad district, Maharashtra, India, known for its historical significance and scenic views. It stands at an elevation of 1357 feet, offering panoramic vistas of the Alibaug region and the Arabian Sea. The fort is accessible via a trek from Khandale village, and features the Siddheshwar Temple, a river, and a waterfall with water cisterns (Pandavkund). </p>
            <p></p>
        </section>

        <section id="Phansad Wildlife Sanctuary" class="section">
            <h2>Phansad Wildlife Sanctuary</h2>
            <img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEgOKM0aij7vMui-_bLw3C053Xlkue7aGByo_2fTmPZwzF9B8ANyeRhI7P_3P8xtujJS7gx2j4_AxgML6YBOkSyO4MhOv9G2Oss2EpGM0zy2G9WeIOKZG_gmzL34Z80Y9VnZRXJWt9zI_eY/s1600/014.JPG" alt="Phansad Wildlife Sanctuary" class="section-image">
            <p>Phansad boasts an impressive variety of plant life with 710 recorded species, including 179 tree species, 66 shrubs, and 141 herbs. The hilltop areas feature evergreen forests with prominent species like Anjan and Phansada, while the slopes showcase dry deciduous forests with species like Ain, Kinjal, Teak, and Mango. The sanctuary is home to a rich diversity of wildlife. Mammals like leopards, hyenas, jungle cats, sambar, barking deer, bonnet macaques, wild boars, and the Malabar giant squirrel are commonly found. Birdwatchers will delight in the presence of 148 species, including the Malabar Pied Hornbill, Black Eagle, Yellow Footed Green Pigeon, and the critically endangered White-rumped vulture. The sanctuary is particularly notable for its herpetofauna, sheltering 31 species of snakes, including the Indian Rock Python and Russell's Viper.</p>
            <p></p>
        </section>
